Australian, N.Z. Stocks: Mount Gibson, Paladin Energy, UGL

-- B y   P h o e b e   S e d g m a n   a n d   L y n n   T h o m a s s o n
-- 
2011-04-29T06:51:29Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-29/bhp-beach-mount-gibson-paladin-energy-rio-ugl-australia-n-z-stocks.html
Australia ’s S&P/ASX 200 Index fell
1 percent to 4,823.20 at the 4:10 p.m. close of trading in
Sydney, bringing its slump during the holiday-shortened week to
1.8 percent. The index slipped 0.3 percent in April, the first
monthly decline since November.  New Zealand’s NZX 50 Index gained 0.4 percent to 3,519.33,
an almost three-year high, at the 5 p.m. close in Wellington.
The measure has risen 0.8 percent this week, adding to a 2.3
percent advance for April.  The following were among the most active shares in the
market today. Stock symbols are in parentheses after company
names.  Mining companies: A measure of primary metals traded in
 London  gained 0.3 percent.  BHP Billiton Ltd. (BHP)  , the world’s No. 1 mining
company, dropped 1 percent to A$45.83.  Rio Tinto Group (RIO AU), the world’s second-largest mining
company by sales, lost 1.4 percent to A$82.21.  Oil stocks: Oil dropped from a 31-month high in  New York ,
trimming an unprecedented eighth monthly gain, as evidence the
global economic recovery is faltering stoked speculation demand
for crude will decline. Futures for June delivery fell as much
as 50 cents to $112.36 a barrel in electronic trading on the  New
York Mercantile Exchange .  Woodside Petroleum Ltd. (WPL)  , Australia’s second-
biggest oil and gas producer, fell 1.8 percent to A$46.80.
 Santos Ltd. (STO)   lost 2.5 percent to A$15.12.  Gold producers: Gold futures surged to a record for the
second straight day after the U.S. Federal Reserve pledged to
keep borrowing costs low, eroding prospects for the dollar and
boosting demand for the metal as an alternative investment.
Futures for June delivery rose $14.10 to $1,531.20 an ounce at
1:49 p.m. on the Comex in New York.  Newcrest Mining Ltd. (NCM)  , Australia’s biggest gold
producer, declined 1.4 percent to A$41.45.  Beach Energy Ltd. (BPT)   fell 5.4 percent to 96.5
Australian cents. The Australian oil and gas producer was cut to
“sell” from “hold” by analysts at Citigroup Inc.  Extract Resources Ltd. (EXT)   tumbled 12 percent to
A$6.68 for the biggest decline in the S&P/ASX 200. The uranium
explorer dropped on concern that Namibia plans to give mining
and exploration rights to a state-owned company.  Goodman Fielder Ltd. (GFF)   gained 1.9 percent to A$1.075.
Australia’s largest baker had its stock rating cut to
“underweight” from “neutral” by analysts at JPMorgan.  Mount Gibson Iron Ltd. (MGX)   declined 1.8 percent to
A$1.88. The iron-ore producer said rain and flooding at some of
its operations caused a 41 percent drop in ore sales in the
three months ended March 31 from the previous quarter.  Paladin Energy Ltd. (PDN)   plunged 4.4 percent to A$3.30.
The uranium producer said that following talks with the Namibian
government, it is “our understanding that the equity position
and operations of Langer Heinrich will remain unaffected” by
reported changes to the country’s mineral policy.  UGL Ltd. (UGL)   fell 3.2 percent to A$15.08. The company
with businesses ranging from engineering to property services
had its stock rating cut to “neutral” from “outperform” by
analysts at Credit Suisse.  To contact the reporters for this story:
